children.project_abstract:
Piezoelectric materials are widely used in our everyday life since this pressure-electricity effect was discovered more than one hundred years ago. This includes cell phones, diesel fuel injectors, ultrasonic transducers, and various vibration sensors. To date, lead zirconate titanate (PZT) based materials is one of the most widely exploited and extensively used piezoelectric materials. However, lead oxide, which is a component of PZT, is highly toxic and causing environmental concerns [1]. Searching for the lead-free, but with a similar performance, piezoelectric materials is very important. So far, one of the very promising materials is the sodium potassium niobate, e.g. K0.5Na0.5NbO3, referred to as KNN. 
  The KNN based materials have been extensively studied in experimental research since the end of 1990s. But it is still a challenge for first-principles study. Recently, the function to calculate the piezoelectric properties have been developed and implemented in the density-functional theory (DFT) based software packages. Here we propose to study the doping effects on the piezoelectric properties of the KNN based materials by using DFT computations. The major methods/codes to be used in the research will be DFT-based VASP and Quantum Espresso packages. 
	The objective of this proposal is to identify and investigate, through the first-principles calculation of the piezoelectric properties, the influence on the KNN-based materials by the various potential dopants. The major computational tasks include:
a)	Determine the most stable K0.5Na0.5NbO3 structure in a given supercell size;
b)	Study the piezoelectric property trend with the composition ratio of K/Na;
c)	Study the origin of enhanced piezoelectricity with different composition;
d)	Cationic dopants such as Li+, Sb5+, Ta5+, Bi3+, Zr4+, Ti4+;
e)	Anionic dopants such as S2-, N3-, Cl-;
f)	Substitutional dopants such as LiTaO3, LiSbO3, CaTiO3, BaTiO3, BaZrO3, Bi0.5Na0.5TiO3;

	The results from this fundamental research will provide guidance to further experimental research and the technology development.

References:
1.	“Review: environmental friendly lead-free piezoelectric materials”, P. K. Panda, J. Mater. Sci. 44, 5049-5062 (2009).
